The function `decode` from `Data.Aeson`, as is clear from [its documentation](https://www.stackage.org/haddock/lts-14.10/aeson-1.4.5.0/Data-Aeson.html#v:decode), returns not the target type (whichever type you&#39;re trying to decode), but the target type wrapped in `Maybe`. In your case, this would be `Maybe [Room]`, not just `[Room]`.

This reflects the fact that decoding might fail (i.e. incorrect format or whatever), in which case the function returns `Nothing`.

This is what the compiler is telling you when it says &quot;_Relevant bindings include: new :: Maybe a0_&quot; - it says that the variable `new` has been inferred to have type `Maybe a0`, where `a0` is some not yet known type. 

It then goes on to tell you that it can&#39;t pass a `Maybe a0` as argument to `start`, because `start` expects the argument of type `[Room]`: &quot;_Couldn&#39;t match expected type [Room] with actual type &#39;Maybe a0&#39; ... in the first argument of &#39;start&#39;_&quot;

To fix this, you need to handle the possibility of `decode` returning `Nothing`, and if it returns `Just`, pass the contents of it to `start`. Something like this:

    load =
       do
       lst &lt;- readFile &quot;savegame.txt&quot;
       let new = decode lst
       case new of
          Nothing -&gt; 
             error &quot;Incorrect file format&quot;
          Just n -&gt;
             start n

(note that calling `error` is not a good way to handle an unexpected condition; I only used it as an example)

