[splice()][1] deletes array elements in-place. When an element is deleted, position of other elements in the array shift. Therefore the indices no longer match on subsequent deletes. That is the reason for unexpected output.

When `splice()` deletes an element, only elements after the deleted element in the array are affected not the ones before it.

So to avoid such index conflicts caused due to in-place deletion, iterate the array in reverse and delete.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let test = [0,1,2,4,5];
    let test2 = [1,2,3,6,5];
    let test3 = [3,4,5,8,9];

    let testCopy = [...test];
    let testCopy2 = [...test2];
    let testCopy3 = [...test3];

    for (let i = testCopy.length - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
      if(testCopy[i] !== 0 &amp;&amp; testCopy[i] !== 2) { 
        testCopy.splice(i, 1);
        testCopy2.splice(i, 1);
        testCopy3.splice(i, 1);
      }
    }

    console.log(testCopy, testCopy2, testCopy3); 

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/splice

